Lovely church. Peaceful. Nice staff. A reminder to us that both communities have their right to peace and quiet.
Such a great idea to host the event like a Belfast Fashion Week in this Cathedral. It looks fabulous from outside and inside
Being a paranormal investigatior , I love looking at these historical buildings . And finding out history, definitely worth a visit
Ignoring the cathedral but there’s some amazing street art here!

Mooi historisch pand aan de markt. Rondleidingen door het pand worden gegeven door Kring Vrienden van 's-Hertogenbosch.  Te boeken via dagjedenbosch.com. Een aanrader.
Beetje ouderwets.

In dit pand is onder andere de Ombudsman van de gemeente 's-Hertogenbosch gevestigd.
Deze Ombudsman is vaak de laatste strohalm die mensen hebben.
Echter is deze commissie niet van fouten verschoond, fouten die zij zelf toegegeven hebben.

Toch weerhouden die fouten hen er niet van om 'over lijken te gaan' en medewerkers van de gemeente die hun boekje te buiten gaan een handje boven het hoofd te blijven houden ! 

Wat in een onprofessionele, bijna corrupte en incompetente organisatie resulteert.
Men zal zich hier uiteraard 'niet in herkennen' maar dat is altijd het standaard rookgordijn dat snel opgetrokken wordt om zaken binnenkamers te houden.
A quiet place for reflection
These people do a great service to the local community, including the local courts. The volunteer run cafe is great.
Quite bright indoors but the outside is easily confused with the law courts and other companies. Parking is a nightmare and very expensive.
I hired the whole venue for an event and was delighted by the facilities, helpful staff and 10/10 location. Thank you!
Wonderful Saxon cross standing in the chancel. Lots of other excellent architectural details to see. Coffee shop sells great cakes!
The Minster is a beautiful building from the ouyside, but I wasn't prepared for how stunning the stained-glass windows are from the inside.
Great place to go in a busy city for a quiet pray
Unfortunately it was closed when I was there, but the building itself looms amazing.
Beautiful building to walk round....Many parts...I saw the remembrance tributes..moving...kind staff made me a cup of tea & I bought a knitted poppy

This church was built more than 150 years ago and hence has historical significance. Even though it is situated at a crowded junction, you can feel the peace once you walk down the path from the entrance to the church. On stepping into it you get to see a glimpse of an era that has been preserved. The peaceful and holy atmosphere is most evident in the afternoon which was the time I chose to visit it.

Right at the heart of the city, this church is a perfect location for worship. Tree covered campus, ample parking space, neatly maintained gardens and buildings. Church is pretty old, still with the old chairs and benches, same old walls and floor. Under renovation now, a new look is expected.

Resting place for the traffic police men while they're not very busy, a breathing space for them.

It was built in 1851, for the British Regiment stationed in Bangalore. 
Built in the English Renaissance style, the church can accommodate 
700 people and is regarded as the largest "military" church in southern India. 
It has a congregation of over 450 families
The church was consecrated on 25 July 1852 and opened on 8 August, 1852. 
The original estimate of the construction was ₹27,000 (US$380)
After Independence, the church was taken over by the Christian Indian Military personnel 
and their families. It was called Holy Trinity Garrison Pastorate then.
The walls were lined with ornate marble murals and tablets, which spoke about 
great men and women who toiled for the church. They Used to conduct many programs for youth especially Troika. They have a best team for youth. On March 10th they conducted the Peace Rally for the Pulwama Terrorist Attack. Really its a good experience for me. I Love this Church

When I moved to Bangalore, my fiancé was going here so he took me here. It was away from where we stay so we started checking other Tamil places nearby but now we are regularly going there. It’s worth traveling there. Best place to worship, such a nice priest. They have a good worshipping culture. You can feel Almighty’s presence there. #myfavchurch
Always a church with deep history and architecture gives a nostalgic feeling. This Tamil church surely is one of the churches which makes me feel at home and gives me a blessed experience.

It's a pleasant bit of green in a one of the nicer areas of central Leeds. It has the potential to be absolutely stunning but it's typical of Leeds council to miss a great opportunity. 
Plenty of benches and bins, this is a little oasis in the quite an industrial city.

Excellent city park. Though feel it's for the privileged. Square is occupied by barristers chambers and garden is tended to daily by the council. Nowhere in the city is given this much care and attention.
A nice area to sit and chill. An oasis of calm in the hustle and bustle of Leeds city.

Old part of Leeds and full of Historic buildings before  newer buildings were erected. On some buildings there are blue plaques which is part of a walk you can go on around Leeds. Look on Internet for information.
Great place to park and relatively cheap in comparison to the rest of Leeds city centre. The machine only takes cash or you can pay via their parking app - parkmobile

I've been a number of times living locally. Huge museum with lots to see and do for all ages. Brilliant to see its using the old wing of the hospital. It really gives a fascinating insight into our medical history. Not the cheapest place around however the ticket price will let you return for year for a free.

A very interesting look at medicine and surgery through the ages. Not overly expensive, and there is a discount for Leeds Card holders.

The tickets last a year, so you can revisit again for no cost.

There is a big refurbishment that is about to take place in 2019, so check whether it is actually open prior to travelling.

This museum keep us reading and seeing displays for nearly four hours could have been longer but car park fee was running out. It is closing for a year for refurbishment which it does need but the  information and displays are really good. It makes one appreciated living in 21st century regarding medical health. At the end is a variety of health activities that the children can participate in. The cafe has been closed and there is only a machine and package food to purchase. A new franchise will be in place when it 're opens next year. I'll certainly go back to view.

Really good museum to visit in Leeds.  Give a vivid view of life was like not so long ago in this area. It is horrifying to see how people lived. It reminded me of London doggone the only difference is that this museum shows the reality of life not so long ago. Very educational.  Great for kids.

A very interesting place to go if you are into learning about the medicines of yesteryear and how they used to do many of the surgical procedures made easy today.
Had a good 2 hours walking around, and then spent time in the cafe that serves pretty fair priced food and drinks for the visitors.
Would recommend this place if you've never been, but once you've been, there is nothing really to come back for a second visit. Not bad entrance fee.

Great place for a family day out. We took the dogs for a walk and ended up walking 7 miles and we did a short walk! You can walk as far as you want and there’s are some beautiful views. Amazing place to take dogs and some very friendly staff and customers. Lots do do also; go ape, farm tour, house tour and many more. If you live a good walk then this is the place for you !!

There was a lot more to see there than I expected. The grounds are incredible and the house is beautiful and fun to see. They had audio tours which was something I had never experienced before. It was a neat, portable, easy to use player and it made the visit all the more memorable and fun.

Temple Newsam is a great place to visit with plenty to see and do. We often go through the week when it is a little more quiet just to walk around the gardens and ponds. The house is worth a look too although it has been a couple of years since I last walked around the house. The house is open everyday except Mondays from 10am to 5pm. The park itself is of course always open although some of the carparks do have barriers which close early evening.
The rare breeds farms is fun whatever age you are and very soon should be running wild with piglets. 
The new Go Ape attraction will be sure to draw the crowds especially if we have a summer like last year. Not had a go myself yet.. still plucking up the courage!
When you need a rest there is a cafe which serves simple food with a choice of hot and cold dishes and close to that there are gift shops selling everything from souvenirs to books and even craft beers. 
There is plenty of parking and disabled access but the old courtyard, where the cafe and gift shops are, is cobbled so care will be needed with wheelchairs and pushchairs.
All in all a good place to visit and if you are looking for sometime out but not wanting to spend too much then definitely give it a go.

We originally went to Temple Newsam to run their Parkrun. However, once there, decided to take a look around. Entrance fee is more than reasonable given there's tours and audio guides included in the cost. We spent 3 hours just looking around the house and on a tour of the cellars. Unfortunately we had to get home but there's enough gardens/grounds to fill an entire day. Lots of walks! The cafe is nice with reasonable pricing too.
Lovely place for all the family, including the dogs - great walks, beautiful scenery and a cafe. The farm and house offer lots to see and do too. We come here often.

I've always wanted to look inside the Abbey but it's always been closed off to the public. But went passed the other day and noticed the gates were open. Went in and it's all been done out. It's so nice to be able to walk around and see it all. They also have some information boards inside the Abbey which tell you a little history of the place. Definitely worth a visit.

A really beautiful place with a lot of history. It's free and you can enjoy it with your family.
Once a month there is a market, they also give meditation and activities for children in the store and in the museum.

A good place to visit especially during morning time (opens at 10 am though). Nice place to take a stroll, walk your dog and have s morning run. 

Nice architecture, canal flowing beside and greenery all around.

A lovely place to visit as a family. Nice cafe opposite, with toilets and baby change. Good playground too, although it is also nice for children to play in the Abbey grounds and take in the ancient architecture. Pleasant river walk nearby.

Absolutely great for a day out of the hustle and bustle of the city of Leeds but amazingly still so close to it! Come in Spring when the park looks amazing. The Abbey itself is pretty impressive. There is a small fee to go inside but it's worth it. A good spot for bringing a picnic and just chilling in the sun.

We had a surprising couple of hours here. Fantastic to see working waterwheels driving shafts and pulleys helping to show how the mill worked. Found things in the house, which you can touch and hold, that we remembered as children.
Nice place to visit for an hour or two. Combine with a walk along the canal. Nice staff including Millie the mill cat.

More than you think. Nice working mill with guided tours. A walk along the canal and meet the friendly boat people. An adventure area for the children with things to build and explore. Nice cycling to Leeds or the other way to Castleford. Narrow boats and barges and an annual water festival in the Summer.
Well worth a visit. Shop selling drinks and snacks and souveniers.
Lots to see and learn about. We were there much longer than I anticipated even though it was a chilly day. Take a picnic as refreshments are limited.
Fascinating industrial museum.  Beautiful setting with river and canal.   Cafe. Parking.  Available for weddings, meetings and events on request.

The Church of St. John the Baptist is one of the oldest churches in Jerusalem, with roots dating back to the mid 5th century. Historically, it has been a Mosque as well as a hospice during the Crusader period. However, presently it is a Greek Orthodox church. 

The exterior of the building is being restored at present, meaning it can't be accessed at Muristan. However, if you walk back to Christian Quarter Road, you'll find a small alleyway leading to the courtyard where the church can be entered and visited. You will notice a small sign which states that the church remains open from 9am to 5pm daily but closed on Sundays. 

Inside you will find darkly lit rooms decorated in early Christian and Greek Orthodox manner. Attractive chandeliers hang from a ceiling and there are nicely painted images to see. Heavily gilded iconostasis and entire walls lined with beautiful iconic images can be seen. The interior is small and can be conveniently enjoyed in 5-10 minutes if you are short on time. 

Overall, The Church of St. John the Baptist is an interesting ancient church that many seem to skip or not know about. We really enjoyed finding and visiting while sightseeing in the Christian Quarter and would gladly return if we were to visit the city again.
January 9 Jesus of Nazareth love you go live hope  in prominent live faith program problem in Jesus come
Currently restoration. Hard to locate but walk along the marketplace till see a small entrance.

Nice place To Visit but  closed

They are closed. The gym I got too is right next door.
Such a nice building it's a waste it's abandoned

Excellent walks, great to take the whole family, nice tea room but I would go early if your partial for a scone like me as they are very high demand and go very fast. Perfect cups of tea, water fizzy pop and stilled drinks available. Nice to go see the ducks

Lovely spot for a walk. There's parking but it does get busy so arrive early if it's a nice day. There's a small cafe with plenty of coffee and cake options. They have some gluten free and vegan snacks too :)
Great place to visit.  Nice walk around even in winter.  Even better in summer . Got good history too. Roll on summer !
Went for the first time had a picnic walk round the pond/lake then fed some squirrels the kids loved it nice place
Really enjoyable walk, great for the kids and to walk your dogs. Plenty of different paths to follow. Get there early as the car park gets very busy when it's a nice day.
My favourite place in the whole world. So much to explore. Beautiful trees and plants. Absolutely magical. Wear wellies! It can be muddy.
Very nice place to walk round. Well kept and nice place to visit. We take the dog there and he l8ves playing ball.
A lovely place to go for a walk and get some fresh air. Also a horticulturalist dream.
Nice Park.  Quiet and tucked away.  Very steep though so not suitable for anyone that can't walk up a steep and muddy hill.
Great places for a dog walk.

The house was very interesting, quite a bit of history about the family. We didn't get a chance to go through the aviary as it closed at 4.15pm which was a shame. Lots of play equipment for the kids though. Parking is a breeze as there are so many parking areas. I think this house and grounds will make a lovely day out for a family. Recommended 😁

We enjoyed looking at all the animals especially the penguins who interacted well with us. The gift shop has a good selection of gifts and toys, all reasonably priced. Unfortunately we weren't impressed with the cafe, the cakes and drinks were poor. Although plenty of space for families and larger parties.

I've been coming here for over twenty years. I love it. Leeds Council are doing a great job and consequently it's becoming  much busier but if you want calmness there's always a quiet corner even at the most popular times. Family season-ticket is great value at about £45 whereas the family day-ticket is about £24. I recommend a picnic at busy times, catering good but quite expensive. Plenty to see and do.

A brilliant day out during half term with the kids. The different birds are lovely for the young children to see and the penguins are probably the highlight of the day. We had snacks in the cafe but probably if we go again in the summer we will take a picnic. Next time we will try and time our visit so we can go round the house as well.

Great day out for all the family with plenty to do. Cafe facilities are available.
Lotherton Hall has a lot to offer, Stately home; gardens; children's play areas;  woodland walks and small zoo visitor  attraction. 

At Christmas Lotherton Hall is a stopping point for Father Christmas and he never fails to disappoint as he brings pine forests and snow with him for his visit.
A beautiful part of the country well worth a ramble
Always a beautiful place for a walk. It's well kept, and the terrain is easy going in most spots. Dog friendly, various spots for parking.
So usually i take the dog out for walks here, the hubby took me off-road in Chevin forest and it was such a good laugh! not sure if this is permitted but who cares it was great :) !!
Love Otley Chevin and so does my Lab
Really nice up here, anywhere around here is a Great walk, with beautiful scenery

It's a nice green space very close to the city center. Great to see volunteers picking up rubbish and keeping the place clean. There's a children's playground, basketball court and a skate park on one corner and ample grassy areas just to chill, have a picnic etc. It's not too big so it'll be a quick stroll around it but nonetheless, a nice place to relax

Bristling with local life on skateboards bikes or just  lounging on the grass there's plenty to see and exotic aromas fill the air in spring and summer. Murders of crows oversee the commute between Hyde Park and the university. Join the community and fight for climate rescue.

Last time l was here was in the late 80's ........used to live in Woodhouse until 1970, left to live in Beckett Park but returned to go to feast whenever on. Large open spaces , great hill for sledging-done that a few times.......and  quite a few pathways to stroll down/round.

Like the area. Has lots of students and a nice big park. Houses look to be pre war era. Near to Leeds University. Has plenty of shops, takeaways etc. Seems to have a variation of students and families with young children.  Around a mile away from the city centre.
Great open public space with skate park and grass fields. Not well lit at night but be sensible and walk around it where the streets are. Great place in the summer with various festivals.

Nice clean and well decorated and looked after hotel. The spa is lovely worth a visit. The drinks in the bar are expensive and the evening menu fairly limited. Worth a visit but  maybe not go back again.

Heating in the room didn't work properly. Got woken up early to the LOUDEST thumping music (assume it was some gym class). Couldn't get the weird pods to work and make a cup of tea. Sound travelled from people slamming doors in the corridor. Not exactly a restful night's sleep.
A truly wonderful hotel. Clean, modern and delicious food. Great gym and spa facilities.
Very nice room. We upgraded and the room was lovely. It had Starbucks coffee in the room and sky channels. Very good price for one night
Stayed for 1 night. Decent room (standard double) with a nice Samsung TV. The restaurant was being renovated so sat in the pub had a burger which was pretty good. I stay here again.

The staff were very welcoming professional and more than happy to help. The food arrived in a timely manner and was very well presented. The meals were flavoursome fresh and cooked to perfection. I would certainly recommend and return. The ambience was lovely and the place was very tastefully decorated.

I'm comparing the menu with what it was a few years ago and they've sold out. Pink peppercorn cream sauce is now just tomato sauce with little cream and no peppercorns in it whatsoever. Tastes like a jar sauce now. San Carlo used to be the best Italian in Leeds. This was not worth the hundred quid for two. Big shame and big disappointment.
Good food. Great atmosphere. Fast service. Overall a great place to fine after busy day.

I and my wife went for lunch and our disappointment was palpable... The wine was awful and the food poorly prepared. My wife chose the fish medley special (on my advice) and suffered 2 day food poisoning.
I have been visiting this restaurant since childhood and am sorry to say it seems now to be the flying pizza in name only...
Very expensive for mediocre to downright poor quality food.
Upsetting...

Gushing waiters pressing for drinks orders. Lovely starter. The main was really a starter portion too. No chance of pepper mill or extra parmesan. Seated under the speaker. Over priced and underwhelming. I have had better here before. I recommend you come for the specials menu as a one off rather than just regular trips for pasta/pizza if you expect better like me.
Very nice staff and the food was excellent. Didn't take long to arrive and was hot and fresh. Pretty consistent ordering at Pizza Express. There is a takeaway option also if you need to dash.
Very good pizza. Perfect service. I will come back for sure ;).
Such good food! At first it looks like a fast food restaurant but the food is really good quality and tasty!
Good pizza, slow service.
Delicious food. Friendly, helpful staff.

The setting, at the side of the lake is excellent.  Although it was at a busy lunch time there was space to sit in comfort.  The food was decent and quickly delivered.  The staff were very pleasant and friendly.  Overall a very good facility well supported by the people if the city.
We were here for a private evening event and it is lovely! A great setting, friendly staff, good facilities and good food. Would recommend.
Brilliant choice for adults and kids. Particularly thrilled about the amount of gluten free options. I've never had a gluten free scone before 😊

Not sure what can be said that hasn't been said already! Great range of food - particularly the decadent selection of sweet things. Great view obviously, which I think looks just as good (if not better) on a rainy or overcast day. Mix of seating inside and understandably it can get a bit noisy when it's busy, so not always ideal for quiet reflection unless you've got noise-cancelling headphones. Walkable from the park entrance (though not quickly) and parking outside. Wheelchair accessible.
I love the view on a sunny day.  The service is so slow and I will never understand the system they use at the counter.  If more than 6 in the queue I give it a miss

Excellent food, quick and friendly service. Top notch. :)

Used to eat here quite often. Paid our first visit in over 5 years for lunch in Bank Holiday Monday. Happy to report that it's still a great experience-delicious food and wine and a lovely friendly atmosphere. Highly recommended.
Come here for past 15 years and never had a problem!

Over rated restraunt no leg space took around a hour to hour and half to bring my pizza. Don't understand why so many people like it much better places like Frank and Bennys in The Light, Bibis is wonderful and both San Carlos.

Always a beautiful meal here and the steak is always perfectly cooked (medium rare). Lovely service, we have a family meal here for most of the big birthdays. Glad Dumfries still has somewhere like this.
Decent. Food was ok but underwhelming... Dishes ordered were chosen with high expectations but minimal flavour coming through and tough meat let it down. Chips were nice. Well presented too.
Delightful  fresh food. Gorgeous  desserts. Friendly  helpful staff.  A nice place to meet friend's  for a relaxing lunch , no time pressure  to vacate the table.
Superb Monday lunch, three courses and a beer with the wife. Brilliant can't recommend highly enough. Good sized portions and fantastic service.
We were down from Edinburgh we had been recommended this restaurant by friends, it is a hidden gem , lovely food , friendly staff and beautiful surroundings, will definitely be back

Absolutely astounding!! Without a doubt some of the nicest food I have ever had. Well done to the owners who have made a great menu for everyone. Having a wheat intolerance and being a veggie I didn't know what to choose it had so many options for me. 11 out of 10 😉 Well done to the the lovely waiting staff, although new were brilliant. When we come back to Leeds expect us again 💚💚💚💚
Really good food.  Friendly efficient staff.  Definitely recommend.  This is a strong 4 star review.

Really enjoyed this restaurant, we have been looking for a decent Mexican for some time and have finally found one. 

The food was very tasty, fresh and not oversized portions. We were served promptly and the food arrived in a good time by pleasant staff, this combined with a nice relaxed atmosphere made for a very enjoyable visit. I wouldn't hesitate to recommend this to friends and are sure we will make another visit.
very good atmosphere, staff, drinks and especially FOOD
Good food with reasonable prices. Nachos can be a great sharing starter.

Came here for a delicious family dinner, on a busy Saturday night.
We had phoned, earlier in the day, and managed to reserve a table for 8 of us.
There was a relaxed, vibrant atmosphere as we walked in, and happily welcomed by the staff.
Really liked the menu, (not to big) which had a selection of starters and mains, big dishes and little dishes.
All the food was flavoured and cooked beautifully, the was nothing that we did not enjoy.
Would happily come back if I was in the area again
Greeted with a friendly warm welcome. Offered a great choice of delicious dishes. Served with a smile and presented with a bill that was amazing value. Looking forward to returning soon.
Great service. The food was very nice for the price. The sea bass was seasoned beautifully and tasted great but the star of the show was the chocolate orange cake, WOW! I highly recommend it.

The food was excellent as always, the relaxed atmosphere with the screen showing a beautiful beach makes you feel like you are in the Mediterranean. Starters we had whitebait & prawn cocktail main meals were lamb shish & pepperoni pizza. Thank you nonce again for a lovely evening.😀

My wife and I decided to have a cheeky lunch out and we picked the Olive Branch. It is a lovely place it has recently been extended and the decor is nice and new but giving a cosy feel. The staff were super friendly and very helpful. They explained the menu and the offers available. They helped us decide and offered nice conversation. The food itself was fresh and nicely cooked, really tasty also.

Nice clean and well decorated and looked after hotel. The spa is lovely worth a visit. The drinks in the bar are expensive and the evening menu fairly limited. Worth a visit but  maybe not go back again.

Heating in the room didn't work properly. Got woken up early to the LOUDEST thumping music (assume it was some gym class). Couldn't get the weird pods to work and make a cup of tea. Sound travelled from people slamming doors in the corridor. Not exactly a restful night's sleep.
A truly wonderful hotel. Clean, modern and delicious food. Great gym and spa facilities.
Very nice room. We upgraded and the room was lovely. It had Starbucks coffee in the room and sky channels. Very good price for one night
Stayed for 1 night. Decent room (standard double) with a nice Samsung TV. The restaurant was being renovated so sat in the pub had a burger which was pretty good. I stay here again.

I've been to Headingley Stadium 3 times to see England play test cricket. Each time, there has been a special buzz in the crowd.

The last visit was England vs. Pakistan and I find it refreshing that a mixed crowd can unite to enjoy the game.

Headingley has evolved over the years but I feel they have the right balance between extending the capacity while keeping the unique character.
In the process of getting a major makeover which will enhance both the Rugby and Cricket stadiums. Hotel on site, good facilities.
Going to be great when it is finished. Plenty of turnstiles, once inside there are plenty of bars and fast food outlets. Always a great atmosphere.
This stadium will be superb when finished, best in Super League, hopefully will have a team to match soon 😁
Great Stadium wasn't a great evening for me my team lost but like I said Great Stadium
Nice cafe. I visited as I was passing just for a relax. Staff were friendly and service was very good. Prices are a little higher than I expected. Overall, no complaints

A great choice for brunch with friends - a good variety of sweet and savoury food and drinks, all well-presented. Everything we had was delicious - I particularly recommend the homemade garlic hummus! 
A good choice of options suitable for vegetarians and vegans as well, so nobody misses out.

Such a nice place for brunch. The staff there is super attentive! The prices are reasonable and the food is delicious! A proper place to have English breakfast, the “LS6 Yorkshire” breakfast is lush, also the pancakes, please treat yourself and order a “nutnana” pancake. I have to go back to Leeds and try more dishes in this place.
Nice hipster bar, live music at times, airy open plan feel. Staff don't seem overly friendly. Not a winner but would go again of in the area
It's always very popular and once you've been you'll see why! The staff were very helpful and the venue is comfortable and clean. There are also plenty of veggie and vegan items on the menu

This place is just Awesome. We love it as a family and have also taken friends. Great food, always delicious. Staff are friendly and helpful as the menu is very big, plenty to choose. Tried some different rums with some help from the bar man. Would very much recommend.

Well worth many return visits for the cocktails alone. Tasty consistent food. Wide variety of dishes. Decent sized portions tapas style food (recommend two to three per person). Won't break the bank. Really excellent cocktails, would go there just for a drink (not sugary sweet like many places). Friendly service. Genuinely one of my favourite restaurants in the UK (food is not Michelin star stuff just reliably good every time).
Absolutely superb, great value.  5 of us went and we had the set price for each. They just kept bringing the tapas dishes out. Brilliant.
Loved viva Cuba,  excellent food, excellent service, Good prices. Ne of our new favourite Tapas places. 5*****
Absolutely love this little gem! Great food, great service and great atmosphere.... can’t keep away!! Highly recommended.
Very nice. Best fish and chips I've had in a long time. Really light tasty batter and perfectly cooked flaky fish. Good friendly service too.
Worst fish and chips Ever! Mum's just thrown up. Greasy and tasteless. No wonder nobody goes there anymore. I tell you what, they should paying us to eat it.

First thing that needs mentioning is that this restaurant has recently changed hands and has a completely new menu and management in place.  But don't let that put you off.

The food was truly outstanding.  We were made to feel so welcomed and was treated like Queens (Corny, I know but so true)

We will definitely be back.
Absolutely first class food. You will not be disappointed. You would be wasting your hard earned money going anywhere else.
What a gem of a place! The food is just delicious, the service was impeccable. A small place but nice layout and finishing. Highly recommended, if attending a cricket game, booking advisable.

I've been here three times. Looks clean and pretty good service, no problems finding a parking spot. The food is good and I would give more stars if they would get my order right. I ordered three orders of veggie rice without egg. Every time at least one of the orders has had egg and even once got egg and chicken. After the second time my SO complained that his rice was crunchy.

Did this place get new owners?  Cash only with an atm in the entryway. (3$ for those who don't carry cash).  We ordered lunch here and the vegetable curry was kind of cold. The rest if the food was cool too. A little heavy on the red pepper so watch the spice level. The food just wasn't the same. Haven't been here in about a year but, it wasn't the same.  Service was ok. Lunch for 2 with soup and an app was 36.00.
Best place to get Thai food..... If you love spicy food come here.... They also have other selection of you don't like spicy food
Food very ordinary.  I love Thai food but this one is near the bottom.  I went with a friend.  Both of our meals were slightly hotter than room temperature.  Pretty boring.  Not recommended.
must be under new ownership. seems the quality of food has changed as well as they are now cash only? not a fan
My favourite Thai place in Leeds, lots of vegan options and everything from spice to sweetness can be made to order. Lovely, welcoming staff and a lovely atmosphere. Can't wait to go back.
Fabulous as always! Great food! Great service and very affordable prices too! You must go if you haven't already!

One of the better Thai places in Leeds. Not ostentatious, but understated in its decor. The food, however, is very good as is the service. They also cater to vegetarian, vegan and gluten-free diets, so make sure you ask for options when you choose your dishes
There are three Thai restaurants in the area and this one is the best. Food was great and value.
Great food, very reasonably priced with a friendly atmosphere.

I have been eating here for the last 35 years. The food is gorgeous (and has always been so - its a husband and wife team that have always run it) - and very reasonably priced. Recommended for anybody who likes good well-flavoured food in a low key pleasant atmosphere. If you like cocktails, Peter the proprietor makes a variety of mean ones.
closed at 1310 on a Wednesday

Expensive unless you can eat your own body weight!  Lovely food.  Wide range of dishes.  Small desserts........just the right size after what we ate!  Staff pleasant and polite even on a busy Thursday evening.  I'd go again........take Tupperware!

Love this place, loads of range of meals, all you can eat and also all you can drink on soft drinks. Seems a little pricey when you arrive, but you can soon get good value for that money you’ve spent. I particularly like the grill which will cook your choice of meat in front of you and to your liking! Well worth a visit!
Really nice place that I last went to 3/4 years ago. Much improved. Food was really tasty and very much improved from the last time. Will be going again.

Been here before as Cosmos and JRC. Nowadays it's lovely inside, clean and calm. However, don't be fooled. The floors are sparkling on the customer side but have a look behind the counters at the drains filled with rubbish, spills and food waste on the floor and generally poor hygiene. Food wise, I've found this place okay previously but our most recent visit was disgusting and we will not be returning. The sweet and sour chicken tasted like Birds Eye Cod from the frozen section of Tesco. I love seafood, but chicken should not taste like fish! Food temps were varied, at best it was warm. We started fresh 3 different times and failed to find anything edible. The thought of the poor hygiene we had seen lingering in our minds really didn't help! Oh yes  and the cherry on top was the guy who served us took the drinks vouchers from us, we were never given glasses and then when we asked for them they were reluctant to give them to us without an argument. Disappointed would be polite!

Went there this afternoon. Shocking, food warm not alot of choice what was there was bland and tasted of fish, so it was cooked in the same place as fish and I did not have any fish not that there was any fish dishes. My brother recommend it said there was a good choice Italian food pasta meat balls etc, there was none of that. Pizza looked as if it had seen better days. I have always tipped, but in this case I did not. It was terrible, will not be going back!!!!!

I love mint so I really loved this museum. It showed the history of the mint industry in Kitami and how the oil is extracted. They also showcase different kind of mints and displays lots of mint related products.
Great place to learn about the mint- making process! The factory was really cool! If there was information in English it would be great!

ハッカについて説明してくれる方がいてわかりやすかったです。
施設は建物が２棟。古いですが西洋風の建物で素敵です。お土産が少し置いてあって、ハッカ飴や、ハッカ豆など試食もありました。
観光に、30分あれば十分見れる感じです。

北見＝薄荷の歴史を知らずに北見観光の一環での訪問でしたが、行って良かったと思える所です。

【記念館】
10月の日曜日でしたがお客さんはまばらでした。ただ、そのおかげでスタッフさんに親切丁寧に庭先に植えられた原料も使いながら説明をしてもらいよく理解できました。
少し古めの展示も懐かしくていいです。

【蒸溜館】
お土産購入のつもりで入館。こちらの展示は少しですがこちらでも親切な説明があったり、お土産の商品一つ一つにもこれは･･･と笑顔で教えてくれました！

その後、２月の雪の季節にも訪問。前回より少ししか経っていなかったので中には入りませんでしたが、買ったハッカ油が切れたら、また必ず行きます！

北見(駅)で１時間半くらい時間があれば行くことをお勧めします。

ハッカ記念館は「薄荷」つまりミント工場の遺構ですね。最近は観光対応を強化したようで、進化した分、1ポイントアップしました。蒸留窯を見て何かに似ていると思った方、それは余市の工場を見学されていると比較できます。基本的にはwhiskeyの製造と同じです。実は江戸時代に灯油を精製した原理と同じです。ハッカの蒸留は工場で行われていただけではありません。ハッカ農家にも蒸留窯の遺物があったのを過去に見た事があります。ハッカ御殿については2017年のBS日テレ「北海道すたいる」という番組で紹介されていました。仁頃地区に現存しているらしいのです。アドヴィックス常呂カーリングホールへの通り道にあると思いますが、放送された木造家屋は私も見覚えがあります。
　蒸留により、水と精油に分かれると説明されると解りにくいのですが、水とアロマオイルに分かれると書くと何～んだ！という事になります。北見市では植物のミントを栽培していますから、高純度の合成ミントとは違った天然アロマオイルの良さがあります。ミントオイルは花粉症の時期には大活躍です。私もハッカのど飴のおかげで症状が緩和されましたが、花粉が目の粘膜に刺さるのは我慢出来ません。痛みは取れないですが、かゆみは出ませんからハッカは重宝ですね！
　＊＊ハッカ記念館は幸町の「ピアソン記念館」と同じ風ぼうです。比べると面白いです。関東地区でも放送がある「ブギヴギ専務」という番組で紹介されていました。＊＊
